1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,079
I was assigned the job of handling all collection correspondence.

2
00:00:02,430 --> 00:00:06,639
The collection letters the store had been using greatly disappointed me.

3
00:00:06,829 --> 00:00:09,600
They were strong, insulting, and threatening.

4
00:00:09,629 --> 00:00:15,280
I read them and thought, Brother, I'd be mad as hell if somebody sent me letters like these.

5
00:00:15,389 --> 00:00:16,720
I never would pay.

6
00:00:16,990 --> 00:00:24,160
So I just got to work and started writing the kind of letter that would move me to pay an overdue bill if I received it.

7
00:00:24,350 --> 00:00:25,280
It worked.

8
00:00:25,469 --> 00:00:32,800
By putting myself in the shoes of the overdue customer, so to speak, collections climbed to a record high.

9
00:00:34,029 --> 00:00:41,840
Numerous political candidates lose elections because they fail to look at themselves through the minds of the typical voters.

10
00:00:42,430 --> 00:00:48,560
One political candidate for a national office, apparently fully as qualified as his opponent,

11
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:52,400
lost by a tremendous margin for one single reason.

12
00:00:52,670 --> 00:00:57,920
He used a vocabulary that only a small percentage of the voters could understand.

13
00:00:58,589 --> 00:01:03,040
His opponent, on the other hand, thought in terms of the voters' interests.

14
00:01:03,069 --> 00:01:06,160
When he talked to farmers, he used their language.

15
00:01:06,350 --> 00:01:11,199
When he spoke to factory workers, he used words they were easily familiar with.

16
00:01:11,389 --> 00:01:18,879
When he spoke on TV, he addressed himself to Mr. Typical Voter, not to Dr. College Professor.

17
00:01:19,550 --> 00:01:21,520
Keep this question in mind.

18
00:01:21,790 --> 00:01:26,240
What would I think of this if I exchanged places with the other person?

19
00:01:26,589 --> 00:01:29,920
It paves the way to more successful action.

20
00:01:30,910 --> 00:01:38,080
Thinking of the interests of the people we want to influence is an excellent thought rule in every situation.

21
00:01:38,510 --> 00:01:44,799
A few years ago, a small electronics manufacturer developed a fuse that would never blow out.

22
00:01:45,070 --> 00:01:52,799
The manufacturer priced the product to sell for $1.25 and then retained an advertising agency to promote it.

23
00:01:53,230 --> 00:01:59,919
The account executive placed in charge of the advertising immediately became intensely enthusiastic.

24
00:02:00,350 --> 00:02:06,480
His plan was to blanket the country with mass advertising on TV, radio, and newspapers.

25
00:02:06,750 --> 00:02:08,320
This is it, he said.

26
00:02:08,430 --> 00:02:11,120
We'll sell 10 million the first year.

27
00:02:11,470 --> 00:02:16,960
His advisors tried to caution him, explaining that fuses are not a popular item,

28
00:02:17,070 --> 00:02:23,440
they have no romantic appeal, and people want to get by as cheaply as possible when they buy fuses.

29
00:02:24,030 --> 00:02:30,240
Why not, the advisors said, use selected magazines and sell it to the high income levels?

30
00:02:30,590 --> 00:02:39,120
They were overruled, and the mass campaign was underway, only to be called off in six weeks because of disappointing results.

31
00:02:40,030 --> 00:02:41,519
The trouble was this.

32
00:02:41,710 --> 00:02:48,720
The advertising executive looked at the high-priced fuses with his eyes, the eyes of a high-income person.

33
00:02:49,070 --> 00:02:54,080
He failed to see the product through the eyes of the mass market income levels.

34
00:02:54,270 --> 00:03:03,680
Had he put himself in their position, he would have seen the wisdom of directing the promotion toward the upper income groups and the account would have been saved.

35
00:03:04,670 --> 00:03:10,030
Develop your power to trade minds with the people you want to influence.
